Color formation in ozonized water has been analyzed, considering both the pH0 (Fig. 4
                        ) and ozone flow-rate ([O3] mg/min), (Fig. 5
                        ) employed during ozonation assays. The aim of this study was to determine whether the degradation route causing color formation consisted of a direct ozone oxidation of paracetamol or, on the contrary, could be attributed to the unselective oxidation by hydroxyl radicals generated through ozone decomposition (pH0 values higher than 6.0). This part of the work was performed operating within an initial pH range of 3.0–12.0 (see Fig. 4). Normalized TOC (mg/L) and absorbance at 254 nm ([Arom], AU) values, together with the color (Color∞, AU) and the ozone mass transfer coefficient (KLa, l/min) determined at the end of treatment have been all represented. The maximum color generated during ozonation experiments has been also included.
